check.description: Checks to determine whether the `allowBackup` flag within the Android Manifest is set to False.
Reverse engineers the applications and checks if the source code has been obfuscated either by Proguard or Dexguard in order to make class identification less obvious.

Determines if an application can be decoded and if its resources can be extracted for further analysis.
Checks for embedded URLs in the source code, which can point to sensitive company servers or assets and provide valuable information to potential attackers.

Applications can use SQLCipher for local storage of user data or other sensitive information. SQLCipher requires initializing a database key which also needs to be generated and stored securely. This test checks for any potential (but unconfirmed) possibility of a SQLCipher database key leakage.
Shows the files contained in the APK package.
Checks for the use of dynamic code loading within the APK.
Checks to determine whether the application was compiled with the `debuggable` flag enabled in the Android manifest.
This checks if the application is attempting to exploit the Master Key vulnerability by having two files with the same path and file name.
This test checks reverse engineered code for any evidence of a SQLCipher database key.
This test checks to see if the key used to sign the app is larger than 1024 bits. Anything less leaves your app vulnerable to forged digital signatures.

Checks for native libraries used in the application.
Native libraries are non-Java libraries typically loaded through Java Native Interface (JNI).
During static analysis, the binary is searched for vulnerable versions of the third-party library OkHTTP.

Reflection grants the ability and flexibility to view and determine API characteristics at runtime, as opposed to compile time.
From there, developers can construct objects, access fields, and invoke methods dynamically.
These reflection APIs come as part of the Android SDK and can be beneficial when targeting a variety of Android versions/devices.
At runtime, reflection techniques can be used to determine if a specific class or method is available before trying to use it.
This enables the developer to leverage newer APIs, while still supporting older versions, all from within the same application.
This check looks for code reflection within the application and returns where reflection is used.
This static check determines whether the certificate is expired or is set to expire within 30 days.
This check statically looks through the reverse engineered code for implementations of the SecureRandom() function.

This test checks the source code to determine if the permissions requested by the application are in fact used by the application.
To do this, the list of requested permissions from the source code is compared to the list of granted permissions.

Determines whether the application is properly validating the Certificate Authority (CA). To verify that Certificate Validation is being properly performed, an attempt is made to intercept network traffic from the app using a certificate that was not signed by a CA (a self-signed certificate). If the certificate is accepted by the app, all data that uses that connection is decrypted.

Determines whether the application is properly verifying that the certificate's hostname matches the intended hostname for the network communication. To verify that Hostname Verification is being properly performed, an attempt is made to intercept traffic from the app using a certificate that was signed by a valid Certificate Authority (CA) and issued for a domain that will not match the endpoint in which the app is establishing a connection with. If the app accepts a CA-signed certificate issued to a mismatched hostname, it may be attributed to issues in the Hostname Verification process. If the certificate is accepted, the traffic is decrypted.

This is an extension of the tests to check for proper Certificate Authority and Hostname verification. If sensitive data is found in the decrypted traffic from either of those tests, it is called out here.

The testing platform attempts to bypass the security controls of TLS communications and provide a window into the data that is being sent within those communications. This test does not provide data on the validity of certificate validation or pinning within an application.

As an example, this finding can be used to identify where sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, GPS coordinates and phone numbers are being sent and auditing that the information is not being sent somewhere that it should not be going.

Applications can use SQLCipher for local storage of user data or other sensitive information. SQLCipher requires initializing a database key which also needs to be generated and stored securely. This test checks for any potential (but unconfirmed) possibility of a SQLCipher database key leakage.
